### Interfaces in C#

An interface defines a contract that implementing classes must follow. It contains declarations of methods, properties, events, and indexers.

### Declaring Interfaces

```csharp
public interface IAnimal
{
    void MakeSound();
    string Name { get; set; }
}

public interface IMovable
{
    void Move();
}
```

### Implementing Interfaces

```csharp
public class Dog : IAnimal, IMovable
{
    public string Name { get; set; }

    public void MakeSound() => Console.WriteLine("Woof!");
    public void Move() => Console.WriteLine("Dog runs");
}
```

### Interface Naming Convention

Interfaces are typically named with an `I` prefix:

```csharp
IComparable, IDisposable, IEnumerable, ICloneable
```

### Default Interface Methods (C# 8+)

Interfaces can provide default implementations:

```csharp
public interface ILogger
{
    void Log(string message);

    void LogError(string message)  // Default implementation
    {
        Log($"[ERROR] {message}");
    }
}

public class ConsoleLogger : ILogger
{
    public void Log(string message) => Console.WriteLine(message);
    // LogError is inherited from interface
}
```

### Explicit Interface Implementation

```csharp
public interface IReader { void Read(); }
public interface IWriter { void Write(); }

public class FileHandler : IReader, IWriter
{
    void IReader.Read() => Console.WriteLine("Reading...");
    void IWriter.Write() => Console.WriteLine("Writing...");

    // Public method
    public void Process() { ((IReader)this).Read(); ((IWriter)this).Write(); }
}
```

### Interfaces vs Abstract Classes

| Feature | Interface | Abstract Class |
|---------|-----------|---------------|
| Multiple inheritance | Yes (multiple interfaces) | No (single base class) |
| Default implementation | Yes (C# 8+) | Yes |
| Fields | No | Yes |
| Constructors | No | Yes |
| Access modifiers | Public by default | All |
| When to use | Capability contract | Related class hierarchy |

### Common .NET Interfaces

```csharp
IDisposable     // Manual resource cleanup
IComparable     // Sorting support
IEnumerable     // foreach support
ICloneable      // Object cloning
IEquatable<T>   // Type-specific equality
INotifyPropertyChanged  // Data binding notifications
```

> **Key Point:** Interfaces define WHAT a class can do, not HOW. A class can implement multiple interfaces. Use explicit interface implementation to resolve conflicts when implementing multiple interfaces with the same method signature. Interface members are public by default.

### Interface Inheritance

```csharp
public interface IShape
{
    double GetArea();
}

public interface IColoredShape : IShape
{
    string Color { get; }
}

public class RedCircle : IColoredShape
{
    public double GetArea() => Math.PI * 25;
    public string Color => "Red";
}

